 The issue in the present case is whether the appellants were denied a fair trial because of the District Judge's alleged bias, and 
not whether the District Judge should have disqualified himself for bias. HN5[
] Judicial disqualification in the federal courts is governed by two sections of the Judicial Code, 28 U.S.C. ยงยง 144, 455 (1982).  Section 144 provides in pertinent part: HN6[
] Whenever a party to any proceeding in a district court makes and files a timely and sufficient affidavit that the 
judge before whom the matter is pending has a personal bias or prejudice either against him or in favor of any adverse 
party, such judge shall proceed no further therein, but another judge shall be assigned to hear such proceeding.

